(47,1,'2023-04-03 16:21:05','2023-04-03 16:21:05','<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"right\",\"id\":12,\"width\":410,\"height\":273,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image alignright size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Mentor-mentee-1-1024x683.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-12\" width=\"410\" height=\"273\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:latest-posts {\"align\":\"center\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2023-04-03 16:21:05','2023-04-03 16:21:05','',2,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=47',0,'revision','',0),
(48,1,'2023-04-03 16:50:17','2023-04-03 16:50:17','<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"right\",\"id\":12,\"width\":410,\"height\":273,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image alignright size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Mentor-mentee-1-1024x683.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-12\" width=\"410\" height=\"273\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Software development freelancing...</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many locations around the globe that are hotspots for software development.   If you happen to live in one of those places, jobs can come looking for you.   But there are many places around the world that have little or no jobs in this field.  In those places you need some extra skills to get and keep work, but it can be done.  This site is a place to find help and to build community of fellow developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Developing your skills</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While traditional full time employment brings a degree of long term job security, freelancers need to keep their current skills fresh in order to stay relevant.  High tech work is constantly changing with new fields opening up almost daily.  Those new fields often have a higher demand for skilled individuals.  Being willing and able to add new leading edge skills will increase your chances to find work and will often pay much better.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Front end web</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The World Wide Web is a rapidly evolving place, and it is a challenging field to stay fresh.   Sometimes there are dramatic shifts in interactive tech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Back end web</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Back end technologies don\'t change as fast as front end, but..</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Full stack</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Working globally</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Building your brand</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Finding work</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Latest Posts</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:latest-posts {\"align\":\"center\"} /-->','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2023-04-03 16:50:17','2023-04-03 16:50:17','',2,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=48',0,'revision','',0),
(49,1,'2023-04-03 18:34:12','2023-04-03 18:34:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Front end, or<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Front-end_web_development\"> front-end web development</a> refers to the skills and technology related to building pages and applications that run in a web browser. The front end development is the part of web development that deals with the user interface(UI) and user experience (UX) of a website. It involves designing and developing the visible parts of the website that users interact with. As a beginner in front-end web development, it is important to learn all of that and follow some best practices to create efficient, and user-friendly web pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of skills to learn in order to be a typical web designer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all of them can be learned at a number of mentor sites.  One of which is <a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">FrontendMentor</a>.  That site (and others like it) have a wealth of information and tutorials that teach you the fundamentals and details of all of these skills.   After reading this page and exploring FrontendMentor some, I recommend you try one of their challenges yourself.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another frontend learning site that is recommended is <a href=\"https://www.freecodecamp.org\">freeCodeCamp</a>.  It not only has many good learning resources but it offers some significant certifications that will show what you have learned and practiced to potential employers or clients. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking ahead, in our page on <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally…</a> there is a challenge to do one of the FrontendMentor challenges and capture your process and final work in a GitHub repository that you can show off what you have learned.   Keep an eye out for that, as it is a very important step in your professional development. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML - Hyper Text Markup Language</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">HTML</a> is a rich markup language which can be viewed and coded in a simple text editing program. It consists of the text to be presented interspersed with HTML markup tags that specify how that text should be displayed. The filename usually ends in either .htm or .html to indicated that it can be displayed in a web browser. The HTML markup standards have been around since the beginning of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web\">World Wide Web.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Here is an example of a HTML document</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":341,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/htm-1024x342.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-341\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As discussed above, all of the above technologies can run on any computer with a web browser. The HTML, CSS files and any embedded JavaScript code can be contained in a text file in a folder on the local computer. You can test this yourself by doing the following challenge:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Instructions:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Create a New File:</strong> Open a text editor like Notepad or a more advanced code editor like Visual Studio Code. Create a new file and save it with the extension <code>.html</code> (e.g., <code>helloworld.html</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Write Basic HTML:</strong> Inside your file, paste the following code:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html>\n&lt;html>\n&lt;head>\n    &lt;title>Hello World!&lt;/title>\n&lt;/head>\n&lt;body>\n    &lt;h1>Hello World!&lt;/h1>\n&lt;/body>\n&lt;/html>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. <strong>Open in a Browser:</strong> Double-click the <code>.html</code> file to open it in your default web browser. You should see a simple webpage with the title \"Hello World!\" and the text \"Hello World!\" displayed in a heading (h1) format.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML5</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\">HTML5</a> is simply the 5th major revision of the HTML standards that added significant modern features that make some web pages very dynamic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML5 is a significant evolution of HTML, introducing new features that enhance web development capabilities. Here are some key aspects:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Semantic Elements:</strong>&nbsp;HTML5 introduces semantic elements like&nbsp;<code>&lt;header&gt;</code>,&nbsp;<code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>,&nbsp;<code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, etc., which provide more meaning to the content beyond just visual presentation. Search engines can better understand the structure of your webpage, aiding in searchability.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Multimedia Support:</strong>&nbsp;Gone are the days of relying solely on plugins like Flash. HTML5 offers built-in support for audio and video elements, allowing direct embedding of multimedia content within web pages.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Offline Capabilities:</strong>&nbsp;Web applications can leverage features like local storage and application cache to store data locally. This enables functionality even when the user is offline, improving user experience.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Improved Forms:</strong>&nbsp;HTML5 provides new input types like&nbsp;<code>email</code>,&nbsp;<code>url</code>,&nbsp;<code>date</code>, etc., simplifying user input validation and enhancing form functionality.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Canvas and SVG:</strong>&nbsp;Developers can create dynamic graphics, animations, and illustrations directly within web pages using the&nbsp;<code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>&lt;svg&gt;</code>&nbsp;elements.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">CSS - Cascading Style Sheets</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS\">CSS</a> is a speciality language for styling text and graphics. While simple HTML can be coded to create the desired look and layout it can be extremely tedious to do so on a large scale. If you are not consistent then the look and feel will be inconsistent. Furthermore, if you decide to change the way your site looks then you will have a monstrous job to adjust all of the tags from start to finish. The intent of CSS is that the raw HTML page should contain the content only. A single reference in the header of the page is made to a .css file that contains the styling directives. If you choose to change the look and feel, then you can code a new css file and change the reference to point to the new one. A further refinement of that idea is with a content management system (CMS) that stores the content in a database. But, that is another subject for another day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Here is an example of a CSS docume</strong>nt</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":351,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/css-1-1024x444.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-351\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Advanced CSS Techniques:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While basic CSS covers fundamental styling, advanced techniques unlock more intricate visual effects and control:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS Preprocessors (Sass, LESS):</strong>&nbsp;These add another layer of abstraction to CSS, allowing you to use variables, mixins, and functions for more maintainable and reusable code.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS Frameworks (Bootstrap, Tailwind CSS):</strong>&nbsp;These pre-built libraries provide pre-defined styles and components, accelerating the development process and ensuring consistency across your web project.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS Grid and Flexbox:</strong>&nbsp;Techniques like CSS Grid and Flexbox offer enhanced flexibility in web page layout. You can define complex layouts with rows, columns, and flexible positioning for a responsive design that adapts to different screen sizes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS Animations and Transitions:</strong>&nbsp;Add interactive elements to your website with smooth transitions and animations triggered by user actions or events.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">JavaScript - A procedural programming language for web pages.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javascript\">JavaScript</a> is a programming language inspired by Java that is meant to run inside a web page.   All of the actual work is performed by the web browser itself. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example of JavaScript</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":345,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/js.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-345\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>JavaScript Frameworks and Libraries:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>JavaScript frameworks and libraries build upon core JavaScript functionalities, providing pre-written code and tools for specific tasks:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Frontend Frameworks (React, Vue.js, Angular):</strong>&nbsp;These frameworks offer a structured approach to building complex user interfaces with features like data binding, component-based architecture, and state management.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>JavaScript Libraries (jQuery, Lodash):</strong>&nbsp;Libraries provide a collection of pre-written functions for tasks like DOM manipulation, animation, asynchronous operations, and utility functions. They simplify common JavaScript operations and promote code reusability.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTTP - Hypertext Transport Protocol</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes, that is all that is needed.  However, that does not make any use of the internet or the World Wide Web.   The \"World Wide\" part of the Web indicates that computers all over the world that are connected to the internet can work together to present a very dynamic universe of information and entertainment.    In order to connect your local computer to any web page in the World Wide Web you simply enter a web address such as <a href=\"http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm\">http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm</a> into the search or address bar of your browser.  The formal name for this address is a URL.  See the wikipedia page <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/URL\">A&nbsp;<strong>uniform resource locator</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>URL</strong>)</a> for details.  The first four characters stand for HyperText Transport Protocol which is one of several protocols as explained in the URL page.  After that the \':\' indicates the beginning of the location of the resource which usually starts with \'//\' followed by the name of the resource.   Try it yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What happened when you pressed return after that address is that your browser used that resource information to find the appropriate web server somewhere in the world (MichaelKentBurns.com) and request a specific page (HelloWorld.htm).  A web server program running on that computer located the file for that page and other associated information and sent it back to your browser running on your computer.  Your browser then formatted it according to the HTML rules and you then see the results.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If, however, you have saved a web page on your local hard drive you would access it using the \'file\' protocol with an address something like this: \"<a>file://C:/Michael/HelloWorld.htm</a>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The details of that is for the next page (<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\">Back end web</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Want to see web development concepts come to life? Dive deeper into the code behind this post! W3Schools (<a href=\"https://www.w3schools.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.w3schools.com/</a>) offers a fantastic interactive learning environment where you can experiment with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Play around with live code snippets, tweak them, and witness the results in real time. This hands-on approach is a great way to solidify your understanding and unlock your creative potential in web development!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Before you move on, remember this roadmap to your career</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A friend of mine who is a reader of this site has contributed a <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/your-front-end-development-journey-a-step-by-step-roadmap/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"299\">roadmap to a Front-End development journey</a>.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Front end web','','publish','open','closed','','front-end-web','','','2024-06-02 21:35:04','2024-06-02 21:35:04','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=49',0,'page','',0),
(50,1,'2024-06-02 19:44:34','2023-04-03 18:34:12',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','50','','','2024-06-02 19:44:34','2024-06-02 19:44:34','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/2023/04/03/50/',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),
(51,1,'2023-04-03 18:34:12','2023-04-03 18:34:12','','Front end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2023-04-03 18:34:12','2023-04-03 18:34:12','',49,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=51',0,'revision','',0),
(52,1,'2023-04-03 18:36:03','2023-04-03 18:36:03','<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"justify\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">Backend development is the server-side aspect of web and software development that focuses on creating the infrastructure, logic, and integration necessary for an application to function properly. It involves working with databases, servers, application logic, and APIs to ensure that the front-end, or client-side, can communicate effectively with the server and perform tasks such as data retrieval, storage, and processing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"justify\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">While the front end is mostly concerned with the actual presentation of web information, there is much that the web browser cannot do. One thing certainly is multitasking. It is rare that a single person, using their browser to view a web page, is the only user at that specific site. The back end is run on a more powerful machine that can server up web pages to many users around the world at the same time. This concept is described in detail in the Wikipedia <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontend_and_backend\">Frontend and backend</a> page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"justify\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">To make the back end work there are actually a number of servers running together that enable many web users to share access to a website. These servers are all run as services by a system administrator and have inter dependancies. So, the various servers have to know how to access each other to get the job done. Since they work together we refer to the whole as a \'stack\'. This is described in detail in the Wikipedia <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LAMP_(software_bundle)\">LAMP (software bundle)</a> page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Key Components of Backend Development</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Server</strong>: The computer or system that runs the backend software. Common server technologies include <a href=\"https://httpd.apache.org/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://httpd.apache.org/\">Apache</a>, <a href=\"https://nginx.org/en/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://nginx.org/en/\">Nginx</a>, and <a href=\"https://www.iis.net/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.iis.net/\">Microsoft IIS</a>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Databases</strong>: Systems that store, retrieve, and manage data. Popular databases include:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SQL Databases</strong>: MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLite</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>NoSQL Databases</strong>: MongoDB, Cassandra, Redis</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Server-Side Languages</strong>: Programming languages used to write the backend logic. Some common ones are:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>JavaScript (Node.js)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)\">Python (Django, Flask)</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)\">Ruby (Ruby on Rails)</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP\">PHP</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)\">Java (Spring)</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>C# (.NET)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(programming_language)\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(programming_language)\">Go</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>APIs (Application Programming Interfaces)</strong>: Mechanisms that allow different software components to communicate. Backend developers often create RESTful APIs or GraphQL APIs to enable interaction between the frontend and backend.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Frameworks</strong>: Tools that provide a structured way to build and deploy applications. Some widely used backend frameworks are:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Express.js</strong> (Node.js)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Django</strong> and <strong>Flask</strong> (Python)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Ruby on Rails</strong> (Ruby)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Spring Boot</strong> (Java)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>ASP.NET Core</strong> (C#)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Essential Skills for Backend Developers</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Programming Proficiency</strong>: Mastery of one or more server-side languages and their associated frameworks.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Database Management</strong>: Understanding how to design, implement, and query databases effectively.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>API Development</strong>: Ability to design and build robust APIs for various client applications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Server Management</strong>: Knowledge of server environments, deployment processes, and scaling applications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Security Best Practices</strong>: Implementing authentication, authorization, data protection, and securing APIs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Version Control</strong>: Using tools like Git to manage code changes and collaborate with other developers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Problem Solving</strong>: Analytical skills to debug issues, optimize performance, and ensure reliability.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Common Tools and Technologies</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Version Control</strong>: <a href=\"https://git-scm.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://git-scm.com/\">Git</a>, <a href=\"https://github.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://github.com/\">GitHub</a>, <a href=\"https://gitlab.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://gitlab.com/\">GitLab</a>, <a href=\"https://bitbucket.org/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://bitbucket.org/\">Bitbucket</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Containerization</strong>: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Docker_(software)\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Docker_(software)\">Docker</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kubernetes\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kubernetes\">Kubernetes</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CI/CD Pipelines</strong>: <a href=\"https://www.jenkins.io/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.jenkins.io/\">Jenkins</a>, <a href=\"https://www.travis-ci.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.travis-ci.com/\">Travis CI</a>, <a href=\"https://circleci.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://circleci.com/\">CircleCI</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Cloud Services</strong>: <a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://aws.amazon.com/\">AWS</a>, <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://cloud.google.com/\">Google Cloud Platform</a>, <a href=\"https://azure.microsoft.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://azure.microsoft.com/\">Microsoft Azure</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Monitoring and Logging</strong>: <a href=\"https://prometheus.io/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://prometheus.io/\">Prometheus</a>, <a href=\"https://grafana.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://grafana.com/\">Grafana</a>, ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Best Practices</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Modular Code</strong>: Writing clean, modular code that is easy to maintain and scale.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Documentation</strong>: Keeping thorough documentation for APIs, codebases, and development processes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Testing</strong>: Implementing unit tests, integration tests, and end-to-end tests to ensure code reliability.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Code Reviews</strong>: Regularly reviewing code with peers to catch bugs and improve code quality.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Scalability</strong>: Designing systems that can handle increased load and user growth efficiently.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Learning Resources</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Books : \"<strong><em>Clean Code</em></strong>\" by Robert C. Martin, \"<strong><em>Designing Data-Intensive Applications</em></strong>\" by Martin Kleppmann</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Online Courses</strong>: Platforms like <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.coursera.org/\">Coursera</a>, <a href=\"https://www.udemy.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.udemy.com/\">Udemy</a>, and <a href=\"https://www.pluralsight.com/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://www.pluralsight.com/\">Pluralsight </a>offer courses on backend development.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Back end web','','publish','open','closed','','back-end-web','','','2024-06-02 21:33:02','2024-06-02 21:33:02','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=52',0,'page','',0),
