(258,1,'2024-02-27 16:42:51','2024-02-27 16:42:51','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael lives near Cedar Park, Texas with his wife Mary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"flexWrap\":\"nowrap\",\"justifyContent\":\"space-between\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":39,\"width\":\"326px\",\"height\":\"244px\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/IMG_1613-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-39\" style=\"width:326px;height:244px\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":169,\"width\":\"324px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/MichaelAtWork-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-169\" style=\"width:324px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael is a 40 year veteran software engineer.  The last 33 years was as a principal systems developer at <a href=\"http://www.sas.com\">SAS Institute</a>.  His main responsibility was the enterprise metadata server that connects all SAS products. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He is now happily retired, but not yet done with the field.  This site is home base for his new focus of mentoring programmers in the art of software engineering.   The main emphasis is individuals living in a places that do not have software development jobs.  This means that their best opportunity is to go freelance.   Doing so allows them to stay in their culture and home community.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While freelancing is a start, there are also opportunities to do so much more as part of a larger development team focused on many open source software projects.   This is something that I am moving into myself.  Join me.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"><!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\",\"service\":\"github\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelkentburns/?lipi=urn%3Ali%3Apage%3Ad_flagship3_feed%3B6Dj3E8auRSy51Ad%2BgA7N%2FQ%3D%3D\",\"service\":\"linkedin\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\",\"service\":\"mail\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.facebook.com/michael.burns.906\",\"service\":\"facebook\"} /--></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->','About Michael','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2024-02-27 16:42:51','2024-02-27 16:42:51','',22,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=258',0,'revision','',0),
(260,1,'2024-02-27 16:45:58','2024-02-27 16:45:58','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael lives near Cedar Park, Texas with his wife Mary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"flexWrap\":\"nowrap\",\"justifyContent\":\"space-between\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":39,\"width\":\"309px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"aspectRatio\":\"1.3360655737704918\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/IMG_1613-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-39\" style=\"aspect-ratio:1.3360655737704918;width:309px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":169,\"width\":\"324px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/MichaelAtWork-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-169\" style=\"width:324px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael is a 40 year veteran software engineer.  The last 33 years was as a principal systems developer at <a href=\"http://www.sas.com\">SAS Institute</a>.  His main responsibility was the <a href=\"https://www.sas.com/en_us/search.html?q=metadata%20server\">enterprise metadata server</a> that connects all SAS products. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He is now happily retired, but not yet done with the field.  This site is home base for his new focus of mentoring programmers in the art of software engineering.   The main emphasis is individuals living in a places that do not have software development jobs.  This means that their best opportunity is to go freelance.   Doing so allows them to stay in their culture and home community.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While freelancing is a start, there are also opportunities to do so much more as part of a larger development team focused on many open source software projects.   This is something that I am moving into myself.  Join me.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"><!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\",\"service\":\"github\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelkentburns/?lipi=urn%3Ali%3Apage%3Ad_flagship3_feed%3B6Dj3E8auRSy51Ad%2BgA7N%2FQ%3D%3D\",\"service\":\"linkedin\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\",\"service\":\"mail\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.facebook.com/michael.burns.906\",\"service\":\"facebook\"} /--></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->','About Michael','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2024-02-27 16:45:58','2024-02-27 16:45:58','',22,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=260',0,'revision','',0),
(265,1,'2024-03-08 23:38:08','2024-03-08 23:38:08','<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Getting to the administrative control panel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How to use GitHub to source control a WordPress site.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','How to administer a WordPress site','','inherit','closed','closed','','111-revision-v1','','','2024-03-08 23:38:08','2024-03-08 23:38:08','',111,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=265',0,'revision','',0),
(266,1,'2024-03-08 23:58:56','2024-03-08 23:58:56','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As mentioned in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally page</a>, GitHub is an excellent way to keep a repository of a software project. A WordPress site is no exception. However, a WordPress site is significantly different than normal software projects in several regards:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>There is a lot of WordPress itself, as well as its Themes and Plugins that are contained in the public_html directory. That is OK, and it\'s worthwhile tracking changes to those files. For one, it is a good way to detect corruption in a site.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The vast majority of the content of a WP site is in posts and pages. When an author writes a blog post or a page of any sort, it does not create any new web pages in public_html. This is a result of the fact that WP contains a powerful CMS (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_management_system\">ContentManagementSystem</a>). A CMS manages the content in a database not a directory full of fully rendered HTML pages. This is discussed more in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">Full stack</a> page. The actual content of a blog post or a page is stored as a separate record in the wp_posts table. Blog posts have a post_type of \'post\' and pages (like this one) have a post_type of \'page\'. There are in fact a number of other things that get stored in the wp_posts table. As a result of these items stored as records in a table, doing the GitHub tracking of the text of a file will not show changes in individual posts or pages.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Dumping the SQL data for source control</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><p>Because the main visible content is stored in a database table it is necessary to extract the individual records of the wp_posts (and other tables) to textual form so the normal GitHub mechanisms can show it in a readable form. As a first step to doing that, I have written a shells script called \'<strong>dumpall</strong>\' that is kept in the public_html directory (for now). That script is run in a shell process on the WP host site before a Git commit and push commands are run to update the GitHub repository. This is step 1 in the GitHub issue #10 of the GitHub repository\'. Later, I will write a program to extract each record of the wp_posts table into a separate text file in a .data/posts directory. It will require some nicer format than a simple SQL dump.</p><br><p>One issue with the <strong>dumpall </strong>script is that the SQL dump for a specific table creates an INSERT statement to create all records into the table, but all of those records are written to a single line.  Thus when GitHub tries to show the differences between subsequent revisions of a file, it looks like one VERY long line with lots of differences.   What I would rather have is an INSERT statement that puts each record on a separate line.   I have written a shell alias that uses the sed command to split that INSERT line into many lines.   Thus, in the .data directory of my GitHub repository you will see the original SQL dump in a file named <strong>wp_posts.sql</strong> and a version with the lines split named <strong>wp_posts.split.sql</strong>.  I am pushing this change on Wednesday April 17th, 2024 so you should see the text of this post will be changed in the <strong>wp_posts.split.sql</strong> file.</p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Dumping the markup for all pages and posts </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to saving the SQL tables generally, I want to export the text of all the Pages and Posts as separate files.   This allows GitHub change tracking to present the textual changes to the posts and pages individually.    To do this I wrote two shell scripts named <strong>dumpPages</strong> and <strong>dumpPosts</strong>.   dumpPages uses the wp command line utility to get each page markup text into a file in the .pages directory.  The file is named <strong>page-&lt;name-of-page&gt;.wpmu</strong> . The .wpmu extension is my extension name for \"Word Press mark up\".    For example <strong>.pages/how-to-use-github-to-source-control-a-wordpress-site.wpmu</strong> contains the markup text of this page.   The dumpPosts command does the same for posts and stores them in the .posts directory. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When these commands are executed in a secure terminal connected to the server running this WordPress site,  then the markup is exposed as text files to the git program.   When I ask git for the status of this local repository I see this: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>[michael]:public_html$ git status<br>On branch main<br>Your branch is up to date with \'origin/main\'.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Changes to be committed:<br>(use \"git reset HEAD …\" to unstage)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>    new file:   .pages/page-blog.wpmu\n    new file:   .pages/page-termius-as-a-secure-interactive-shell-and-file-transfer-client.wpmu\n    new file:   .posts/post-post-7-process-improvements-stick.wpmu</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Changes not staged for commit:<br>(use \"git add …\" to update what will be committed)<br>(use \"git checkout -- …\" to discard changes in working directory)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>    modified:   .data/wp_commentmeta.split.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_commentmeta.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_comments.split.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_comments.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_links.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_options.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_postmeta.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_posts.split.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_posts.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_usermeta.split.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_usermeta.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_users.split.sql\n    modified:   .data/wp_users.sql\n    modified:   .pages/page-development-platforms.wpmu\n    modified:   .pages/page-how-to-do-easy-time-estimates.wpmu\n    modified:   .pages/page-how-to.wpmu\n    modified:   .pages/page-sample-page.wpmu</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<p>[michael]:public_html$ git diff .pages/page-how-to.wpmu<br />\ndiff --git a/.pages/page-how-to.wpmu b/.pages/page-how-to.wpmu<br />\nindex ed4ba26..2e8c3f7 100644<br />\n--- a/.pages/page-how-to.wpmu<br />\n+++ b/.pages/page-how-to.wpmu<br />\n@@ -4,7 +4,7 @@<br />\n <!-- /wp:list-item --></p>\n<p> <!-- wp:list-item --><br />\n-</p>\n<li><img class=\"wp-image-420\" style=\"width: 30px;\" src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/New.jpg\" alt=\"\"><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/how-to-do-easy-time-estimates/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"404\">How To Do Easy Time Estimates</a></li>\n<p>+</p>\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/how-to-do-easy-time-estimates/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"404\">How To Do Easy Time Estimates</a></li>\n<p> <!-- /wp:list-item --></p>\n<p> <!-- wp:list-item --></p>','How to use GitHub to source control a WordPress site','','publish','open','closed','','how-to-use-github-to-source-control-a-wordpress-site','','','2024-06-02 22:01:45','2024-06-02 22:01:45','',111,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=266',2,'page','',0),
(267,1,'2024-03-08 23:58:56','2024-03-08 23:58:56','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As mentioned in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally page</a>, GitHub is an excellent way to keep a repository of a software project.  A WordPress site is no exception.   However, a WordPress site is significantly different than normal software projects in several regards:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>There is a lot of WordPress itself, as well as its Themes and Plugins that are contained in the public_html directory.   That is OK, and it\'s worthwhile tracking changes to those files.  For one, it is a good way to detect corruption in a site. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The vast majority of the content of a WP site is in posts and pages.   When an author writes a blog post or a page of any sort, it does not create any new web pages in public_html.   This is a result of the fact that WP contains a powerful CMS (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_management_system\">ContentManagementSystem</a>).   A CMS manages the content in a database not a directory full of fully rendered HTML pages.   This is discussed more in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">Full stack</a> page.   The actual content of a blog post or a page is stored as a separate record in the wp_posts table.  Blog posts have a post_type of \'post\' and pages (like this one) have a post_type of \'page\'.  There are in fact a number of other things that get stored in the wp_posts table.     As a result of these items stored as records in a table,  doing the GitHub tracking of the text of a file will not show changes in individual posts or pages.   </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because the main visible content is stored in a database table it is necessary to extract the individual records of the wp_posts (and other tables) to textual form so the normal GitHub mechanisms can show it in a readable form.    As a first step to doing that, I have written a shells script called \'dumpall\' that is kept in the public_html directory (for now).  That script is run in a shell process on the WP host site before a Git commit and push commands are run to update the GitHub repository.    This is step 1 in the GitHub issue #10 of the GitHub repository\'.  Later, I will write a program to extract each record of the wp_posts table into a separate text file in a .data/posts directory.   It will require some nicer format than a simple SQL dump.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','How to use GitHub to source control a WordPress site','','inherit','closed','closed','','266-revision-v1','','','2024-03-08 23:58:56','2024-03-08 23:58:56','',266,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=267',0,'revision','',0),
(269,1,'2024-03-09 00:01:38','2024-03-09 00:01:38','<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Getting to the administrative control panel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/how-to-administer-a-wordpress-site/how-to-use-github-to-source-control-a-wordpress-site/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"266\">How to use GitHub to source control a WordPress site</a>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','How to administer a WordPress site','','inherit','closed','closed','','111-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 00:01:38','2024-03-09 00:01:38','',111,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=269',0,'revision','',0),
(271,1,'2024-03-09 00:17:19','2024-03-09 00:17:19','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the front end is mostly concerned with the actual presentation of web information, there is much that the web browser cannot do.   One thing certainly is multitasking.  It is rare that a single person, using their browser to view a web page, is the only user at that specific site.  The back end is run on a more powerful machine that can server up web pages to many users around the world at the same time.   This concept is described in detail in the Wikipedia <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontend_and_backend\">Frontend and backend</a> page. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make the back end work there are actually a number of servers running together that enable many web users to share access to a website.    These servers are all run as services by a system administrator and have inter dependancies.  So, the various servers have to know how to access each other to get the job done.  Since they work together we refer to the whole as a \'stack\'.   This is described in detail in the Wikipedia <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LAMP_(software_bundle)\">LAMP (software bundle)</a> page. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Web Server (Apache)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">PHP</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">MySQL</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Mentoring</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many mentoring and tutorial sites available.  Just google \"backend mentor\" or view Wikipedia\'s \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontend_and_backend\">Frontend and backend</a>\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Back end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','52-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 00:17:19','2024-03-09 00:17:19','',52,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=271',0,'revision','',0),
(273,1,'2024-03-09 13:12:21','2024-03-09 13:12:21','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have read some of this site it is good to put some of that to a test with a challenge.    There are often several paths that will get you to one of these challenges.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you complete a challenge tell me what you learned and what questions you still have.   For now, we can do that through email and later we can get more formal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Please make sure that you report your experience.</strong>  To do this, create an email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.  Start your email by copying the text of the challenge into your message.   Make the subject of your email, the title of the challenge (from the top of the page).  Then as you follow the steps, simply insert your comments, questions, and problems encountered.   Complete the email with a summary of what you learned.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, dive in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-yourself-so-i-know-how-i-can-help-you/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"181\"><strong>Tell me about yourself </strong>so I know how I can help you.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\"><strong>Tell me about your development setup</strong>,</a> what you already can do, and what you want to be able to do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\"><strong>Setup your own GitHub account</strong> and install Desktop GitHub app.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"222\"><strong>Take any development challenge </strong>and record your work in a GitHub repository.</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lots more to come... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Take a challenge','','inherit','closed','closed','','178-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:12:21','2024-03-09 13:12:21','',178,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=273',0,'revision','',0),
(274,1,'2024-03-09 13:13:31','2024-03-09 13:13:31','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have read some of this site it is good to put some of that to a test with a challenge.    There are often several paths that will get you to one of these challenges.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you complete a challenge tell me what you learned and what questions you still have.   For now, we can do that through email and later we can get more formal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Please make sure that you report your experience.</strong>  To do this, create an email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.  Start your email by copying the text of the challenge into your message.   Make the subject of your email the title of the challenge (from the top of the page).  Then as you follow the steps, simply insert your comments, questions, and problems encountered.   Complete the email with a summary of what you learned.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, dive in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-yourself-so-i-know-how-i-can-help-you/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"181\"><strong>Tell me about yourself </strong>so I know how I can help you.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\"><strong>Tell me about your development setup</strong>,</a> what you already can do, and what you want to be able to do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\"><strong>Setup your own GitHub account</strong> and install Desktop GitHub app.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"222\"><strong>Take any development challenge </strong>and record your work in a GitHub repository.</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lots more to come... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Take a challenge','','inherit','closed','closed','','178-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:13:31','2024-03-09 13:13:31','',178,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=274',0,'revision','',0),
(276,1,'2024-03-09 13:15:42','2024-03-09 13:15:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please write an email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a> (following the instructions on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>) and include these things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your name and email address, as well as any other contact info like Facebook, LinkedIn, Twitter,  Discord, GitHub or other profiles you might have. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Where you live and what your city or country is like.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your education.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your development training and experience.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your career experience and goals. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What your hobbies are.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What kind of development you have already done.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What you would like to learn to do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is another challenge for you to tell me about your current development setup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: Tell me about yourself so I know how I can help you.','','inherit','closed','closed','','181-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:15:42','2024-03-09 13:15:42','',181,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=276',0,'revision','',0),
(277,1,'2024-03-09 13:16:50','2024-03-09 13:16:50','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You may wish to start by reading my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/development-platforms/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"175\">Development platforms</a> page then come back here and tell me about your current setup in an email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a> (following the instructions on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tell me about: </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your computer model, memory, disk, processor.   </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Additional screens you have attached.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your internet access and how it works for you.   What you can and cannot do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Your operating system and release.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What browser(s) you use.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you use a command line tool/shell and which one?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you use a simple text editor or a graphical editor or IDE?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you use GitHub or other site to publish your work?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you use command line git to commit and push work or do you use a program like GitHub Desktop or other graphical tools?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you host your finished work so it is visible to the public? </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What do you like best about your current setup?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What don\'t you like, or what could be better? </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: Tell me about your development setup.','','inherit','closed','closed','','184-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:16:50','2024-03-09 13:16:50','',184,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=277',0,'revision','',0),
(279,1,'2024-03-09 13:19:47','2024-03-09 13:19:47','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally</a> page I discuss the importance of using GitHub to make yourself known and show off your talents.  It is also a great place to discover other projects that you can learn from and teams that you can participate in. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don\'t forget to send me an email (following the instructions on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>) to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Go to <a href=\"http://GitHub.com\">GitHub.com</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read up on what it is and how it works.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Click the \'Sign up\' button and create yourself a free account. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search around for projects that interest you and get a feel for how they are layed out.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Visit my page:  <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns</a> and checkout some of my repositories.   One you might find interesting is <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/MichaelKentBurns.com\">MichaelKentBurns.com</a> which is the project which is the repository for this site.   Yes, I keep an entire WordPress site captured in a repository.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Also checkout the repository in which I captured the process I went through in developing my next challenge:  <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component\">Challenge-Interactive-rating-component</a>, look at the text of the file Notes.md to see how I did it. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Note that the GitHub site is where the public facing copy of your repository is stored.  But, you don\'t want to do your work there, in fact you can\'t.  Instead the idea is that you create a copy of that repository locally on your own machine and develop in that copy.     There are two ways to upload your progress at each step on the way.  One is the original \'git\' cli command.   That requires a little learning which is not a bad idea.  But there is a companion Desktop app that looks a lot like the GitHub.com site.  It is called <a href=\"https://desktop.github.com/\">GitHub Desktop</a>.  You can download that from this link now and install it.  Alternatively, once you have created your first repository and want to \'clone\' it to your desktop machine, the cloning process will offer to install the desktop app for you and feed it the command to do the copy of your new repository.   </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>To get a feel for how this works, take the time to create a \'my first repo\' repository and clone it to your desktop machine.   Then code a simple \'HelloWorld.html\' page.  If you are not familiar with \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%22Hello,_World!%22_program\">Hello, World!</a>\" checkout the wikipedia page.  There you will find source for this simple starter app in almost any language known, including HTML.   When you have coded it, then use the desktop app to commit that and push it to your public repository.   </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Once you have it working locally and have pushed it to the GitHub site you can actually create a \'GitHub Page\' to publish the working page for the whole world to see.   To do that when looking at the repository in GitHub.com, you will see a number of tabs along the top:  \'&lt;&gt; Code\', \'Issues\', ... \'Settings\'.   Pick the Settings.   It will automatically fill in the repository name, and the Default branch will probably be set to \'main\'.    On the left side of the screen in the sidebar, under \'Code and automation\' there is an item named \'Pages\'.  Pick that.   Once there it\'s pretty easy.  Under \'Source\' there is a selector to pick the branch.   That should already say \'Deploy from a branch\'.   Leave that as it is.  Below that is a section labeled \'Branch\'.  In there are two buttons that should say \'None\' and \'Save\'.  It is not real obvious but click the \'None\' button and select the \'main\' branch\'.  Finally press the \'Save\' button.   It should then tell you \'Your GitHub Pages site is currently being built from the&nbsp;<code>main</code>&nbsp;branch.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://docs.github.com/articles/configuring-a-publishing-source-for-github-pages/\">Learn more about configuring the publishing source for your site</a>.\'  In a few moments you can refresh that page and see a note near the top that says something like \'Your site is live at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.github.io/Hello-World/\">https://michaelkentburns.github.io/Hello-World/</a>Last&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Hello-World/actions/runs/7922504847\">deployed</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<img width=\"14\" height=\"14\" src=\"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5041124?s=28&amp;v=4\" alt=\"@MichaelKentBurns\"><a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">MichaelKentBurns</a>&nbsp;1 minute ago\'.   Just click that link or the \'Visit site\' button. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Now that it is published live, you can make a small change to your local copy of the program and commit and push that to GitHub and within a short time your change will be live.   On the right side of the repository page, near the bottom you will see a section labeled \'Deployments\'.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You have probably done this now!  Congratulations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don\'t forget to finish your email with a link to your new repository.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: Setup your own GitHub account and install Desktop GitHub app.','','inherit','closed','closed','','187-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:19:47','2024-03-09 13:19:47','',187,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=279',0,'revision','',0),
(281,1,'2024-03-09 13:23:09','2024-03-09 13:23:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your task is to create a new repository for doing a tutorial project (of your choosing) and capturing your work step by step in that repository.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don\'t forget to <a href=\"mailto: MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">send me an email</a> with that link and a writeup of what you learned, what problems or questions you had.   Don\'t forget to follow the instructions for that email on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have already done that myself using a simple FrontEndMentor challenge.   I captured the whole process in a file called Notes.md in that repository.  Find the link to my repository below.  So, go to my repository and locate the Notes.md file.   You can look around in my repository to see the code I downloaded, the tasks that I decided I needed (called Issues in GitHub terms) and the step by step work to the completed project.   I also used GitHub Pages to publish the end result for the world to see.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is my project repository:   <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/\">https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: capture a tutorial project in a GitHub repository','','inherit','closed','closed','','222-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:23:09','2024-03-09 13:23:09','',222,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=281',0,'revision','',0),
(283,1,'2024-03-09 13:26:36','2024-03-09 13:26:36','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your task is to create a new repository for doing a tutorial project (of your choosing) and capturing your work step by step in that repository.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don\'t forget to <a href=\"mailto: MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">send me an email</a> (following the instructions on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>) with a link to your new repository, a writeup of what you learned, and what problems or questions you had.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have already done that myself using a simple FrontEndMentor challenge.   I captured the whole process in a file called Notes.md in that repository.  Find the link to my repository below.  So, go to my repository and locate the Notes.md file.   You can look around in my repository to see the code I downloaded, the tasks that I decided I needed (called Issues in GitHub terms) and the step by step work to the completed project.   I also used GitHub Pages to publish the end result for the world to see.  Make sure you do the same for your new project. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is my project repository:   <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/\">https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: capture a tutorial project in a GitHub repository','','inherit','closed','closed','','222-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 13:26:36','2024-03-09 13:26:36','',222,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=283',0,'revision','',0),
(284,1,'2024-03-09 15:31:42','2024-03-09 15:31:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The initial construction process is complete enough that I\'m ready for a soft opening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I welcome visitors and would greatly appreciate feedback.  After you have looked around a bit and think this might be helpful to you, please let me know.  On posts like this you can simply leave a comment.  It should also give you the option to subscribe when you submit the comment.  You can also subscribe on the bottom of the side bar.  Lastly you can simply email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get far enough to find one of my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenges </a> please engage and let me know how it goes for you.   Each challenge should include a request to send me a detailed email, and I would greatly appreciate it if you do so.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I still have a lot of writing to do so please check back often.   My writing will be prioritized around what you find valuable.  I\'m happy to revise any of it to make it more valuable to you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, for now, have a look around. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to my mentoring site!','','inherit','closed','closed','','229-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 15:31:42','2024-03-09 15:31:42','',229,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=284',0,'revision','',0),
(286,1,'2024-03-13 16:46:57','2024-03-13 16:46:57','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Basic necessities in a development platform:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Computer</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Internet access</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Web browser</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>File management - either GUI and/or command line commands.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Text editor</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Source management and distribution system</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Collaboration applications</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While those are the basics, you will likely also need:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Web hosting service</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Interactive Development Environment (IDE)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Remote development shell</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Common platforms:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ll not bother to describe all the many programs needed for each of these platforms since that will be found in the Development Tools page.   Rather, I\'ll discuss some of the unique attributes of each and how they relate.   You have probably already chosen a favorite platform, but may also be considering some alternatives.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Linux</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all web hosting servers are running Linux so ultimately if you are going to do full stack development you will need to learn Linux.   Many developers have chosen to also use Linux as their local work computer.  We will discuss hosting servers a little later on this page, but for now we will consider Linux as a local development computer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Linux of course can be installed on PC\'s and Macintoshes.   It can be installed in a virtual machine on either of those platforms.   It also can run native on Windows using <a href=\"https://cygwin.com\">Cygwin</a> which gives an existing Windows user the ability to use both Windows apps and Linux apps interchangeably.   That also eases the Linux learning curve.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>MacOS is based on Unix and the Mac Terminal app depends on Unix (Linux) shells for line mode interactive commands.   There are many different shells available to choose from, but the most commonly used one in my experience is BASH.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you choose to run Linux as your native OS then you will almost always use a graphical user interface.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Windows</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With Windows you naturally have a graphical interface including Windows Explorer,  a web browser like InternetExplorer or Edge, an interactive command line tool like PowerShell or cmd.exe.   Using your browser there are applications galore that you can download and install.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition as mentioned above you can also install <a href=\"https://cygwin.com\">Cygwin</a> and get lots of Linux goodies as well.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Macintosh</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As mentioned above MacOS is really UNIX under the covers.   The Terminal window runs many different UNIX shells.   Many common development tools are available for download and install and ready for use.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, since Terminal gets you into the core of UNIX there are many UNIX, and Linux package managers available that will let you install just like you are in Linux.  Homebrew is one option.   Just Google \'<a href=\"https://duckduckgo.com/?hps=1&amp;q=package+managers+for+mac&amp;ia=web\">package managers for mac</a>\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Web hosting servers</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Most servers are virtual machines in a cloud server farms.   These are almost always headless meaning there is no display and keyboard.   You must access  these using some form of secure shell.   Checkout a google of \'<a href=\"https://duckduckgo.com/?q=ssh&amp;t=osx&amp;ia=web\">ssh</a>\'.   ssh and many programs that use it require secure certificates to be generated and installed on your local machine.  I will have a whole \'How to\' page dedicated to secure networking. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">How about you? </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Give all of those options you probably already have a development platform of some sort and it\'s now time to talk about it.     I need to know about your setup, your needs, and your questions.    I have a \'<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\">Tell me about your development setup</a>\' challenge page that you can use to tell me all about it.   So, go there and tell me.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Development platforms','','inherit','closed','closed','','175-revision-v1','','','2024-03-13 16:46:57','2024-03-13 16:46:57','',175,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=286',0,'revision','',0),
(289,1,'2024-03-28 20:57:14','2024-03-28 20:57:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Front end, or<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Front-end_web_development\"> front-end web development</a> refers to the skills and technology related to building pages and applications that run in a web browser.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of skills to learn in order to be a typical web designer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all of them can be learned at a number of mentor sites.  One of which is <a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">FrontendMentor</a>.  That site (and others like it) have a wealth of information and tutorials that teach you the fundamentals and details of all of these skills.   After reading this page and exploring FrontendMentor some, I recommend you try one of their challenges yourself.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking ahead, in our page on <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally…</a> there is a challenge to do one of the FrontendMentor challenges and capture your process and final work in a GitHub repository that you can show off what you have learned.   Keep an eye out for that, as it is a very important step in your professional development. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML - Hyper Text Markup Language</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">HTML</a> is a rich markup language which can be viewed and coded in a simple text editing program.   It consists of the text to be presented interspersed with HTML markup tags that specify how that text should be displayed.   The filename usually ends in either .htm or .html to indicated that it can be displayed in a web browser.  The HTML markup standards have been around since the beginning of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web\">World Wide Web.</a>  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML5</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\">HTML5</a> is simply the 5th major revision of the HTML standards that added significant modern features that make some web pages very dynamic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">CSS - Cascading Style Sheets</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS\">CSS</a> is a speciality language for styling text and graphics.   While simple HTML can be coded to create the desired look and layout it can be extremely tedious to do so on a large scale.   If you are not consistent then the look and feel will be inconsistent.  Furthermore, if you decide to change the way your site looks then you will have a monstrous job to adjust all of the tags from start to finish.   The intent of CSS is that the raw HTML page should contain the content only.   A single reference in the header of the page is made to a .css file that contains the styling directives.   If you choose to change the look and feel, then you can code a new css file and change the reference to point to the new one.    A further refinement of that idea is with a content management system (CMS) that stores the content in a database.  But, that is another subject for another day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">JavaScript - A procedural programming language for web pages.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javascript\">JavaScript</a> is a programming language inspired by Java that is meant to run inside a web page.   All of the actual work is performed by the web browser itself. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As discussed above, all of the above technologies can run on any computer with a web browser.  The HTML, CSS files and any embedded JavaScript code can be contained in a text file in a folder on the local computer.   You can test this yourself by creating a simple web page in a text editor (Notepad or TextEdit) and storing it on your hard drive.  Cut and paste this in your favorite text editor into a file called HelloWorld.htm:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;HTML&gt;\n&lt;H1&gt;Hello World!&lt;/H1&gt;\n&lt;/HTML&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then using your file browser (Windows explorer or Mac Finder) to locate that file and open it as you would any other document. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTTP - Hypertext Transport Protocol</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes, that is all that is needed.  However, that does not make any use of the internet or the World Wide Web.   The \"World Wide\" part of the Web indicates that computers all over the world that are connected to the internet can work together to present a very dynamic universe of information and entertainment.    In order to connect your local computer to any web page in the World Wide Web you simply enter a web address such as <a href=\"http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm\">http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm</a> into the search or address bar of your browser.  The formal name for this address is a URL.  See the wikipedia page <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/URL\">A <strong>uniform resource locator</strong> (<strong>URL</strong>)</a> for details.  The first four characters stand for HyperText Transport Protocol which is one of several protocols as explained in the URL page.  After that the \':\' indicates the beginning of the location of the resource which usually starts with \'//\' followed by the name of the resource.   Try it yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What happened when you pressed return after that address is that your browser used that resource information to find the appropriate web server somewhere in the world (MichaelKentBurns.com) and request a specific page (HelloWorld.htm).  A web server program running on that computer located the file for that page and other associated information and sent it back to your browser running on your computer.  Your browser then formatted it according to the HTML rules and you then see the results.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If, however, you have saved a web page on your local hard drive you would access it using the \'file\' protocol with an address something like this: \"<a>file://C:/Michael/HelloWorld.htm</a>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The details of that is for the next page (<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\">Back end web</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Front end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2024-03-28 20:57:14','2024-03-28 20:57:14','',49,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=289',0,'revision','',0),
